// Notes:
// -IDEA: use the number line to get implicit judgments of the point estimate below current granularity!
// -REMEMBER TO SAVE ALL RELEVANT VALUES: lastresponsedisplayed and lastresponse

*********************************************
************************* EXPERIMENT EXPTs **
*********************************************
// =====================================================================
// prove_eksp: DISABLED — Quick test experiment for development.
// Uncomment to re-enable for smoke testing.
// =====================================================================
// <expt prove_eksp>
// / preinstructions = (intro1)
// / blocks = [1=demografiBlock;2=learning_histBlock;3=testlearn_histoBlock;4=learnvisualanalogueblock1;5=learnvisualanalogueblock2;6=restaurantInstructionBlock;
//             7=experienceonlyAposskew;8=predictnext5expVisAna;9=distributionunderstandingcheck;10=evaluateBlock;11=textboxlastBlock]
// </expt>

// =====================================================================
// FULL EXPERIMENT: 3 (information type) x 2 (granularity) = 6 between-subjects conditions
// Skew (positive vs negative) is counterbalanced between subjects within each condition,
// yielding 12 groups total. Inquisit auto-assigns group 1-12 round-robin.
//
// Groups 1-2:   Experience only,              low granularity  (0-10 scale), pos/neg skew
// Groups 3-4:   Experience only,              high granularity (0-1000 scale), pos/neg skew
// Groups 5-6:   Description only (histogram), low granularity, pos/neg skew
// Groups 7-8:   Description only (histogram), high granularity, pos/neg skew
// Groups 9-10:  Both (experience + histogram), low granularity, pos/neg skew
// Groups 11-12: Both (experience + histogram), high granularity, pos/neg skew
//
// NOTE: Description-only uses the placebo distribution (modeANDcondition=2),
// which draws from probabilitiesplacebo regardless of posskew. The skew
// counterbalancing for description groups is included for design symmetry
// but has no effect on the stimulus distribution.
//
// Block sequence per condition:
//   1. Demographics
//   2-3. Learn histogram (with knowledge test/retry loop)
//   4-5. Learn response scale (two practice trials)
//   6. Task introduction
//   7. Gain experience (45 trials with attention checks)
//   8. First round of 5 predictions
//   9. Survey about distribution understanding (mean, mode, max, min)
//   10. Evaluation (reveal each prediction vs actual + rate satisfaction, smiley VAS)
//   11. Second round of 5 predictions
//   12. Evaluation (reveal each prediction vs actual + rate satisfaction, smiley VAS)
//   13. Final debrief and comments
// =====================================================================

*****************************************
************************* EXPERIMENT ****
*****************************************

